of employment from 2001 through 2015. </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">43 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>ITW Irish Pension Plan </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Irish Pension Plan operates under a traditional annuity formula (a normal retirement benefit equal to 1.5&nbsp;percent of final average annual pay for each year of
credited service). The final average annual pay is the highest consecutive pensionable base salary over any three-year period over the last ten complete years of service. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Nonqualified Pension Plan </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The
Nonqualified Pension Plan is maintained to make up for benefits that cannot be paid under the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> Pension Plan due to Internal Revenue Code limitations on the amount of compensation that may be
considered and the amount of benefit that may be paid. The Company has not considered awarding additional years of service to executive officers under the plan and, therefore, does not currently have a policy on such awards. For the most part, the
Nonqualified Pension Plan uses the same formulas and other computation elements as the Pension Plan with certain exceptions, including the following: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The Pension Plan uses net compensation after deferrals under the Executive Contributory Retirement Income Plan (the &#147;ECRIP&#148;), and the Nonqualified Pension Plan uses total eligible compensation (generally,
salary and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-equity</FONT> incentive compensation). </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The Nonqualified Pension Plan provides that a participant who leaves the Company, other than upon retirement, may forfeit any plan benefits based on eligible compensation above the IRS maximum amount ($270,000 in 2017)
that may be recognized under a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> plan. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">In addition to the annuity and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">lump-sum</FONT> options available under the Pension Plan, a participant in the Nonqualified Pension Plan may elect to receive fixed monthly installments
over 2 to 20 years. If the executive left employment prior to death, disability or retirement, or if the plan is terminated in conjunction with a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> the
benefit from the Nonqualified Pension Plan would be paid as a lump sum. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Nonqualified Deferred Compensation
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company&#146;s ECRIP offers designated executives an opportunity to defer a portion of their salary and earned
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-equity</FONT> incentive to a deferred compensation account to receive the employer contributions they would otherwise receive if such deferrals had been made under our
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> Savings and Investment Plan and IRS limits did not apply. Deferred amounts receive a rate of interest based on the monthly Moody&#146;s Long-Term Corporate Bond Yield Average (the
&#147;Moody&#146;s Rate&#148;). All of the NEOs are eligible for the ECRIP. An ECRIP participant may defer from 6&nbsp;percent to 50&nbsp;percent of his or her salary and from 6&nbsp;percent to 85&nbsp;percent of his or her variable Cash components
(EIP and Performance Cash), with the applicable matching contribution on the salary and EIP amounts under the Savings and Investment Plan formula (in lieu of any matching contributions under that plan). Salary and EIP deferrals under the ECRIP
reduce the compensation that may be recognized under the Savings and Investment Plan and the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> Pension Plan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The
ECRIP features include a maximum limit on the amount of interest under the Moody&#146;s Rate that would be recognized (12&nbsp;percent annualized, or 15.6&nbsp;percent for amounts eligible to receive 130&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate), a
return of deferral feature whereby an individual could elect to receive a return of the principal amount deferred after a period of at least five years, and options for payment following death, disability or retirement as a lump sum or in monthly
installments over 2 to 20 years. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Retirement under the ECRIP is defined as having attained age 55 with at least 10 years of service, or age 65 with at least 5 years
of service. If an ECRIP participant&#146;s employment ends due to retirement, </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">44 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
death, or disability, amounts deferred to the ECRIP prior to January&nbsp;1, 2010 will receive interest crediting of 130&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate. Amounts deferred to the ECRIP after
December&nbsp;31, 2009 are only eligible to receive 100&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate. During 2017, the Moody&#146;s Rate applied to ECRIP accounts ranged from 3.95&nbsp;percent to 4.24&nbsp;percent for amounts eligible for 100&nbsp;percent
of the Moody&#146;s Rate, and 5.14&nbsp;percent to 5.52&nbsp;percent for amounts eligible for 130&nbsp;percent of Moody&#146;s. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If terminated in conjunction with a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> participants would receive their ECRIP as <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">a&nbsp;lump-sum</FONT> payment. </P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom491986_26"></A>Potential Payments upon Termination </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Payments and benefits received by NEOs upon termination are
governed by the arrangements described below and quantified at the end of this section. We have estimated the amounts involved assuming that the termination became effective as of December&nbsp;29, 2017, the last business day of fiscal year 2017.
The actual amounts to be paid out can only be determined at the time of the NEOs&#146; departure from the Company. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">No payments or benefits are automatically
payable to NEOs upon a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> and if there is a qualifying termination following a
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> there are no tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-up</FONT> payments. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Annual Executive Incentive Plan </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The
Executive Incentive Plan (&#147;EIP&#148;) provides that if a participant is employed as of the last day of the fiscal year, he or she would receive any amounts earned under the Executive Incentive Plan for that fiscal year. In the event an NEO
becomes permanently disabled or dies, the NEO would be eligible for a possible payout under the Executive Incentive Plan. If termination of employment other than for death, disability, retirement or <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> occurs prior to the last day of the fiscal year, a participant forfeits his or her award; however, the Compensation Committee has the discretion to award an amount prorated for the portion
of the fiscal year that the participant was employed. Actual amounts earned based on performance by the NEOs in 2017 are discussed in more detail above in &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis &#151; Components of the 2017 Executive
Compensation Program &#151; Annual Executive Incentive Plan.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>ITW Retirement Accumulation Plan and Nonqualified Pension Plan
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">NEOs who are terminated for any reason receive their benefits under the ITW Retirement Accumulation Plan and Nonqualified Pension Plan as described
in the Pension Benefits table above. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Executive Contributory Retirement Income Plan </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">NEOs who are terminated for any reason receive contributions and accumulated earnings as outlined in the Nonqualified Deferred Compensation section above. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">46 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Long-Term Incentive Plan Awards </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Stock Options and PRSUs: In the event of a termination upon death or disability, all unvested options and PRSUs held by the NEOs would immediately vest. In the event of
a termination upon retirement, unvested PRSUs awarded more than one year prior to retirement would immediately vest, and unvested options and PRSUs awarded within one year prior to retirement would become 25&nbsp;percent vested, with PRSU payouts
subject to achievement of performance metrics. Retirement is defined as a combined age and service of 70, subject to a minimum age of 55 and a minimum service of 5 years. Unvested options will continue to vest according to the original vesting
schedule instead of immediately vesting in the event of a recipient&#146;s retirement more than one year after the grant date of the award. Messrs.&nbsp;Santi and Mr.&nbsp;Nagarajan meet the retirement criteria for the 2015, 2016 and 2017 awards as
of December&nbsp;31, 2017. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In the event of a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> options and 2015 and
2016 PRSUs that are continued or replaced would only vest upon a termination of employment after the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control.</FONT></FONT> Unvested options and PRSUs that are not replaced
would fully vest. In the case of PRSUs, all such vesting events are subject to the achievement of performance goals. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">2015 and 2016 LTI Cash/2017 PSUs and
Performance Cash: In the event of a termination upon death or disability, the awards would vest based on the actual performance level achieved and be paid after the end of the performance period. In the event of a termination upon retirement
(defined as a combined age and service of 70, subject to a minimum age of 55 and a minimum service of 5 years), the awards would vest <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rata</FONT> and be paid after the end of the performance period. In the event
of a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> an award that is not replaced will vest <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rata</FONT> at the greater of target or actual achievement level. In
the event of an actual or constructive termination following a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> an award that has been replaced would vest
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rata</FONT> and be paid at the target level (or actual achievement level if greater). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For all NEOs, in the event of a
termination other than upon retirement, death, disability or a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> any unvested options, PRSUs, PSUs, Performance Cash and LTI Cash held on such date by
the NEOs would be forfeited. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-in-Control</FONT></FONT> Severance
Policy </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company&#146;s 2011 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-in-Control</FONT></FONT> Severance
Compensation Policy provides that, upon an actual or constructive termination following a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> of the Company, the NEOs and other elected officers would be
entitled to receive: (i)&nbsp;two times annual cash compensation (base salary plus average annual incentive pay over the prior three years); (ii)&nbsp;a prorated amount of that year&#146;s annual incentive bonus at the target level (or actual
achievement level if greater); and (iii)&nbsp;a prorated amount of the value of any LTI Cash or Performance Cash awards at the target level (or actual achievement level if greater). We do not gross up any of the compensation paid in the event of
termination due to a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control.</FONT></FONT> </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">47 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(4)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Vesting is limited to the extent that the performance level for the award is achieved. If the minimum performance level is not achieved, the award is forfeited. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(5)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Awards that are replaced after a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> do not receive accelerated vesting. Double-trigger vesting occurs for awards that are
continued or replaced if actual or constructive termination occurs within two years of a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> of the Company. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(6)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Pro-rata</FONT> vesting is at the greater of target or actual achievement level. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom491986_28"></A>Termination and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-in-Control</FONT></FONT> Payments and Benefits </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows the value of payments and benefits
that the NEOs would receive pursuant to the 2011 Long-Term Incentive Plan, the 2015 Long-Term Incentive Plan and the 2011 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-In-Control</FONT></FONT> Severance Compensation Policy
upon retirement, involuntary termination without cause, death, disability or a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> assuming that termination occurred as of the last business day of
fiscal 2017. It also shows the Company&#146;s severance benefits that would be payable to the NEOs and that are available to employees generally. For purposes of this table, LTI Cash and Performance Cash payments are assumed at target level. The
value of unvested stock options, if accelerated upon a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> or termination, is&nbsp;determined using the excess, if any, of $166.85 (the closing price of
ITW common stock on December&nbsp;29, 2017) over the option exercise price. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Santi and Mr.&nbsp;Nagarajan met the retirement criteria for various grants
under the Long-Term Incentive Plan during 2017. The 2015 and 2016 PRSUs, 2017 PSUs, Performance Cash and LTI Cash awards vest and are payable after the performance goals have been met. The unvested stock options continue vesting. In addition,
75&nbsp;percent of the 2017 stock option awards would be forfeited since the assumed retirement occurs within the award year. The PSUs, LTI Cash and Performance Cash awards would be <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rated</FONT> based on the
retirement date. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Voluntary termination without good reason is not shown in the table because such a termination would not trigger the payment of severance benefits
or annual long-term incentives. Stock options, PRSUs, PSUs and LTI Cash awards and Performance Cash awards, whether vested or unvested, are subject to forfeiture if the holder competes with, or divulges confidential information about, the Company,
or if the Compensation Committee determines that the holder engaged in gross misconduct or conduct that is against the business interests of the Company. Awards granted after January&nbsp;1, 2011 are also subject to forfeiture, in whole or in part,
in order to comply with applicable law, regulation, stock exchange, accounting rule, or our clawback policy. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom491986_29"></A>Compensation Committee Report </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Compensation Committee of the Board of Directors hereby
furnishes the following report to the stockholders of the Company in accordance with rules adopted by the Securities and Exchange Commission. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and
discussed with management the Compensation Discussion and Analysis contained in this proxy statement. Based on our review and discussions, we have recommended to the Board of Directors that the Compensation Discussion and Analysis be included in
this proxy statement and the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2017. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">This report is submitted on behalf of the members of the Compensation Committee: </P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Includes directors&#146; deferred shares, and shares subject to RSUs, PRSUs and PSUs. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom491986_31">
</A>Pay Ratio </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As required by
Section&nbsp;953(b) of the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act, and Item 402(u) of Regulation <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">S-K,</FONT> we are providing the following information about the ratio of the annual total
compensation of the median ITW employee to the annual total compensation of our CEO. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The pay ratio reported below, in our view, is a reasonable estimate calculated
in a manner consistent with SEC rules, and is based on the methodologies and assumptions described below. SEC rules identifying the median employee and determining the pay ratio permit companies to employ a wide range of methodologies, estimates and
assumptions. As a result, the pay ratio reported by other companies, which may have utilized other permitted methodologies or assumptions, and which may have a significantly different workforce structure from ours, are likely not comparable to our
CEO pay ratio. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company has an extensive global footprint in 56 countries and approximately 50,000 employees, of which approximately <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">two-thirds</FONT> are outside of the U.S. Compensation practices in these countries vary and we pay our employees based on competitive practices within each location. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In 25 countries, ITW has small employee populations. We therefore chose to apply the de minimis exemption, as permitted by the SEC, and excluded countries which, in the
aggregate, make up approximately 4% of our total workforce. The countries excluded are as follows: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="70%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="0%"></TD>
<TD nowrap style="width:40pt"></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD nowrap style="width:40pt"></TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#00416a" STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Countries</FONT></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" COLSPAN="4" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:2pt"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT
 COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Excluded Employees</FONT></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">(in each
country)</FONT></B></FONT></P></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt">Austria, Estonia, Indonesia, Luxembourg, Peru, Turkey</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" COLSPAN="4" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">Less&nbsp;than&nbsp;15&nbsp;employees</TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#d8d8d8" STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt">Chile, Columbia, Croatia, Finland, Guatemala, Hong Kong, Norway, Philippines, Puerto Rico, Singapore, South Africa, Switzerland, United Arab
Emirates</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" COLSPAN="4" NOWRAP ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">Less&nbsp;than&nbsp;100&nbsp;employees</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt">Argentina, Costa Rica, Hungary, Ireland, Portugal, Thailand</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" COLSPAN="4" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">Less than 200 employees</TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">To calculate the pay ratio, we identified the median employee based on our employee population as of October&nbsp;31, 2017, which was
approximately 50,000 employees, before excluding approximately 2,000 employees by applying the exemption noted above. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">52 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">To identify the median employee, we collected employees&#146; regular pay (salary or hourly wages), overtime pay and
shift differentials/premiums, and pay received for paid time off. For employees who participate in a company-sponsored defined contribution retirement plan, we also included their company-paid contribution. We did not include annual incentives or
bonuses, sales incentives or commissions, long-term cash or equity incentives, allowances, or any benefits received as part of a company-sponsored defined benefit pension plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">With this information collected, we identified 20 employees whose compensation we believe is around the median of all employees and we then identified the actual annual
total compensation for each of these employees in order to determine the final median employee compensation. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our median employee compensation is $40,738. As set
forth in the Summary Compensation Table, the total compensation for our CEO for 2017 is $17,109,870. Accordingly, the pay ratio between our CEO and median employee is 420:1. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">53 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom491986_32"></A>Certain Relationships and Related Party
Transactions </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We review related-party transactions in accordance with our Statement of Principles of Conduct,
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> and Corporate Governance Guidelines, rather than a separate written policy. A related-party transaction is a transaction involving the Company and any of the following persons: a director, director
nominee or executive officer of the Company; a holder of more than 5% of ITW common stock; or an immediate family member or person sharing the household of any of these persons. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Statement of Principles of Conduct states that our directors, officers and employees must avoid engaging in any activity, such as related-party transactions, that
might create a conflict of interest or a perception of a conflict of interest. These individuals are required to raise for consideration any proposed or actual transaction that they believe may create a conflict of interest. Our <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> provide that no related-party transaction is void or voidable solely because a director has an interest if (1)&nbsp;the material facts are disclosed to or known by the Board of Directors and the transaction
is approved by the disinterested directors or an appropriate Board committee comprised of disinterested directors, (2)&nbsp;the material facts are disclosed to or known by the stockholders and the transaction is approved by the stockholders, or
(3)&nbsp;the transaction is fair to the Company as of the time it is approved. Our Corporate Governance Guidelines provide that the Board will apply established Categorical Standards for Director Independence in making its independence
determinations. Under the standards, certain relationships between the Company and a director would preclude a director from being considered independent. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">On an
annual basis, each director and executive officer completes a Directors&#146; and Officers&#146; Questionnaire, which requires disclosure of any transactions with the Company in which he or she, or any member of his or her immediate family, has a
direct or indirect material interest. The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee reviews the results of these questionnaires and discusses any related-party transaction disclosed therein. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In addition, under its charter, the Audit Committee is responsible for reviewing, approving, ratifying or disapproving all proposed related-party transactions that, if
entered into, would be required to be disclosed under the rules and regulations of the SEC. In reviewing related-party transactions, the Audit Committee considers the factors set forth in our Statement of Principles of Conduct, <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> and Corporate Governance Guidelines, as well as other factors, including the Company&#146;s rationale for entering into the transaction, alternatives to the transaction, whether the transaction is on terms
at least as fair to the Company as would be the case were the transaction entered into with a third party, and the potential for an actual or apparent conflict of interest. No member of the Audit Committee having an interest in a related-party
transaction may participate in any decision regarding that transaction. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We maintain a commercial banking relationship with The Northern Trust Company and its wholly
owned subsidiaries. The Northern Trust Company is a wholly owned subsidiary of Northern Trust Corporation and beneficially owns approximately 6.5% of our common stock. Ms.&nbsp;Susan Crown and Messrs. Jay L. Henderson and David&nbsp;B. Smith, Jr.,
directors of the Company, are also directors of Northern Trust Corporation and The Northern Trust Company. In 2017, The Northern Trust Company provided the following services to the Company: credit services, treasury and investment management
services, trade services, credit enhancement or payment guaranty, acting as agent or fiduciary, consulting services, risk management services, securities lending services and broker dealer services. In addition, The Northern Trust Company serves as
the trustee under the Company&#146;s principal U.S. pension plans. The banking and trustee relationships with The Northern Trust Company are conducted in the ordinary course of business on an <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">arm&#146;s-length</FONT>
basis. Banking, investment management, trustee and other administrative fees paid to The Northern Trust Company or affiliates by the Company were approximately $4.0&nbsp;million in 2017. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">54 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom491986_33"></A>Audit Committee Report </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee of the Board of Directors is composed of five independent directors, as defined in the listing standards of the New York Stock Exchange, and the
Board of Directors has determined that all Audit Committee members are &#147;financially literate.&#148; In addition, the Board of Directors has determined that Messrs.&nbsp;Brutto and Henderson meet the Securities and Exchange Commission criteria
of &#147;audit committee financial expert.&#148; The Audit Committee operates under a written charter adopted by the Board of Directors, which was most recently reviewed by the Audit Committee in February 2018. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee is responsible for providing oversight to the Company&#146;s financial reporting process through periodic meetings with ITW&#146;s independent
registered public accountants, internal auditors and management in order to review accounting, auditing, internal control and financial reporting matters. The Audit Committee is also responsible for assisting the Board in overseeing: (a)&nbsp;the
integrity of the Company&#146;s financial statements; (b)&nbsp;the Company&#146;s compliance with legal and regulatory requirements; (c)&nbsp;the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s qualifications, independence and performance;
(d)&nbsp;the Company&#146;s overall risk policies and practices; and (e)&nbsp;the performance of the Company&#146;s internal audit function. Company management is responsible for the preparation and integrity of the financial reporting information
and related systems of internal controls. The Audit Committee, in carrying out its role, relies on Company senior management, including senior financial management, and ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following is the report of the Audit Committee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and discussed
with senior management the audited financial statements of the Company. Management has confirmed to the Audit Committee that the financial statements have been prepared in conformity with generally accepted accounting principles. We have also
reviewed and discussed with Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP, ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm, its audit and opinion regarding the Company&#146;s financial statements. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and discussed with senior management their assertion and opinion regarding the Company&#146;s internal controls. Management has confirmed to the Audit
Committee that internal controls over financial reporting have been appropriately designed and are operating effectively to prevent or detect any material financial statement misstatements. We have also reviewed and discussed with
Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP its audit and opinion regarding the Company&#146;s internal controls. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and discussed with Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche
LLP the matters required to be discussed by PCAOB Auditing Standard No.&nbsp;1301 (Communications with Audit Committees) under which Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP must provide us with additional information regarding the scope and results of its
audit of the Company&#146;s financial statements. This information includes: (1)&nbsp;Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP&#146;s responsibility under generally accepted auditing standards; (2)&nbsp;significant accounting policies; (3)&nbsp;management
judgments and estimates; (4)&nbsp;any significant audit adjustments or internal control matters; (5)&nbsp;any disagreements with management; and (6)&nbsp;any difficulties encountered in performing the audit. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have received from Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP a letter providing the disclosures required by applicable requirements of the Public Company Accounting Oversight
Board regarding the independent accountant&#146;s communications with the Audit Committee concerning independence with respect to any relationships between Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP and the Company that in its professional judgment may
reasonably be thought to bear on independence. Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP has discussed its independence with us, and it has confirmed in the letter that, in its professional judgment, it is in a position to serve the Company as its Independent
Registered Public Accounting Firm. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee also discussed with the Company&#146;s internal auditors and independent registered public accounting firm
the overall scope and plans for their respective audits. The Audit Committee </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">55 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
meets periodically with the internal auditors and independent registered public accounting firm, with and without management present, to discuss the results of their examinations, their
evaluations of the Company&#146;s internal controls, and the overall quality of the Company&#146;s financial reporting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Based on the reviews and discussions
described above, we recommended to the Board of Directors, and the Board approved, the inclusion of the audited financial statements in the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for the year ended
December&nbsp;31, 2017, for filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:69%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Pamela B. Strobel, Chair </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:69%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Daniel J. Brutto </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:69%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Jay L. Henderson </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:69%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Richard H. Lenny </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:69%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">David B. Smith, Jr. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">56 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom491986_34"></A>Proposal 2 - Ratification of the Appointment of
Independent </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Registered Public Accounting Firm </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee is directly responsible for the appointment, compensation, retention and oversight of the independent registered public accounting firm retained to
audit ITW&#146;s financial statements. The Audit Committee is also directly involved in the selection of the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s lead engagement partner in conjunction with the mandatory rotation of the lead
engagement partner. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee has engaged Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP (&#147;Deloitte&#148;) to serve as ITW&#146;s independent registered public
accounting firm for the fiscal year ending December&nbsp;31, 2018. Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP has been employed to perform this function for the Company since 2002. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Audit Fees </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Deloitte, the member firms of
Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu, and their respective affiliates (collectively, the &#147;Deloitte Entities&#148;) will bill us approximately $10,450,000 for professional services in connection with the 2017 audit, as compared with $9,646,000 for the 2016
audit of the annual financial statements and internal controls. These fees relate to: (i)&nbsp;the audit of the annual financial statements included in our Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K;</FONT> (ii)&nbsp;the review of
the quarterly financial statements included in our Quarterly Reports on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-Q;</FONT> (iii)&nbsp;the internal controls audit; and (iv)&nbsp;statutory audits. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Audit-Related Fees </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">During 2017 and 2016,
the Deloitte Entities billed us approximately $54,000 and $155,000, respectively, for audit-related services. These fees relate to work performed with respect to technical accounting assistance and comfort letters related to debt issuances. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Tax Fees </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">These fees include work
performed by the Deloitte Entities for 2017 and 2016 with respect to tax compliance services such as assistance in preparing various types of tax returns globally ($1,476,000 and $1,215,000, respectively) and tax planning services, often related to
our restructurings and new tax rules ($677,000 and $517,000, respectively). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>All Other Fees </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">There were no fees for other services rendered by the Deloitte Entities for 2017 and 2016. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Audit Committee <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Pre-Approval</FONT> Policies </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee has adopted policies and procedures for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approval</FONT> of all audit and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> related work to be performed by ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm. As a part of those procedures, the Audit Committee performs a qualitative analysis of all <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> work to be performed by our independent registered public accounting firm. Each year, the Audit Committee receives a detailed list of the types of audit-related and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> related services to be performed, along with estimated fee amounts. The Audit Committee then reviews and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approves</FONT> audit work and certain categories of tax
and other <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services that may be performed. In conducting its analysis, the Audit Committee carefully contemplates the nature of the services to be provided and considers whether such services:
(i)&nbsp;are prohibited under applicable rules; (ii)&nbsp;would result in our accountants auditing their own work; (iii)&nbsp;would result in our accountants performing management functions; (iv)&nbsp;would place our accountants in a position of
acting as an advocate for the Company; or (v)&nbsp;would present a real risk of a conflict of interest or otherwise impair our accountants&#146; independence. The Audit Committee also annually <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approves</FONT> the
budget for annual GAAP, statutory and benefit </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">57 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
plan audits. Company management provides quarterly updates to the Audit Committee regarding <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">year-to-date</FONT></FONT>
expenditures versus budget for audit and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services. The Audit Committee also considers whether specific projects or expenditures could potentially affect the independence of ITW&#146;s independent
registered public accounting firm. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee annually reviews Deloitte&#146;s independence and performance in determining whether to retain Deloitte or
engage another firm as our independent registered public accounting firm. In the course of these reviews, the Audit Committee considers, among other things: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
